Who Lives At the Bonneville Salt Flats?¶

This project uses metagenomic data that was already run through quality control, assembled, and annotated prior to these steps. Read mapping was also performed to obtain abundace information of various genes investigated here. This work identifies species performing crucial roles in ecosystem functioning and investigates potential differences in metabolic processes across and within the 8 sites sampled.

Publications related to this work:
McGonigle, J.M., Bernau, J.A., Bowen, B.B., Brazelton W.J., 2021. Metabolic Potential of Microbial Communities in the Hypersaline Sediments of the Bonneville Salt Flats, in review
McGonigle, J.M., Bernau, J.A., Bowen, B.B., Brazelton W.J., 2019. Robust Archaeal and Bacterial Communities Inhabit Shallow Subsurface Sediments of the Bonneville Salt Flats, mSphere 4:4 e00378-19

Data Used:
Data is publicly available under: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/bioproject/PRJNA522308

A note on the data:
Metagenomic data contains genetic information of all cells and free DNA in the enviornmental sample. It represents a total community view. The abundance data used here is represenative of the entire microbial community. The MAGs (or bins) are sequences that are computationally pulled from the bulk data that have enough relation to each other to represent individual species genomes. These programs use methods like k-means clustering and genomic information such as GC-content and abundance to group related sequences together. Therefore the MAGs can give us a species-level look at the data, while the metagenomes give us a total-population-level look at it.

Exploring Abundance of Microbial Metabolisms Across the BSF¶

Read mapping produced values for fragments per kilobase (FPK) for each gene. There are many ways to normalize abundance data, a good review can be found here: https://www.rna-seqblog.com/rpkm-fpkm-and-tpm-clearly-explained/. I normalize for gene length and sequencing depth to compare abundance of interesting genes across samples. This means the FPK needs to be converted to FPM (fragments per kilobase million), also known as TPM with RNA-Seq data.

Convert FPK values to FPM/TPM, add more gene infomation by combining with KEGG reference list, save outputs for plotting

#################### Convert FPK to TPM ########################################

## Process one column at a time. Function calculates TPM for each column.
ColumnTPM <- function(dataframe,i) {
  # Store column fpk counts into a list
  fpkList <- dataframe[1:nrow(dataframe),i]
  # Calculate scaling factor for column/sample
  denom <- sum(as.numeric(dataframe[,i]))/1e6
  # Do maths and convert all fpk values to tpm
  colList <- do.call(c, lapply(fpkList, function(e){
    tpm <- as.numeric(e)/denom
    return(tpm)
  }))

    return(colList)
  
}

dfTPM <- do.call(data.frame, lapply(2:ncol(dfSamples), ColumnTPM, dataframe=dfSamples))

# Copy the column names from the original dataframe, add back the KEGG_ID column
colnames(dfTPM) <- colnames(dfSamples[,-1])

dfTPM <- cbind(dfTPM, dfSamples$KEGG_ID)
colnames(dfTPM)[17] <- 'KEGG_ID'

########################## Write BubblePlot() Functions ##################################
SampleNitPathBubblePlot <- function(dataframe){
  # return a bubble style plot for a gene abundance per Sample and Sample Grouping
  # Inputs: dataframe = raw data frame of gene abundance data formatted with colnames: Name, Sample, Group, tpm
  
  cols <- c('Name', 'Group')
  dataframe[cols] <- lapply(dataframe[cols], factor)
  
  #Order x-axis samples, remove points for samples with zeros 
  SamplePlot <- dataframe[which(dataframe$tpm>0),] %>%
    mutate(Sample = fct_relevel(Sample, 
                                "D35.1","D33.1","D29.1","D56.1","D46.1","D12B.1","D67B.1",
                                "D33.2","D29.2","D46.2","D12B.2","D67B.2",
                                "D35.2","D35.3","D56.2","D56.3"),
           Name = fct_relevel(Name,
                              "napA","napB","narI","narG","narH", "nirS", "nirK", "norB","norC","norD",
                              "norQ", "nosZ", "nirB","nirD","nrfA","nrfH")) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=Sample, y=Name))
  
  ##Plot ggplot2 object, size bubbles is tpm, color is gene
  BubblePlot <- SamplePlot + 
    geom_count(aes(size=tpm, color=Pathway)) +
    theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
          panel.background = element_blank(), axis.line = element_line(colour = "black")) +
    scale_size(range = c(1,15))
  
  return(BubblePlot)
  
}

SampleCPathBubblePlot <- function(dataframe){
  # return a bubble style plot for a gene abundance per Sample and Sample Grouping
  # Inputs: dataframe = raw data frame of gene abundance data formatted with colnames: Name, Sample, Group, tpm
  
  cols <- c('Name', 'Group')
  dataframe[cols] <- lapply(dataframe[cols], factor)
  
  ##Make $Pathway column
  
  rbcList <- c('rbcS','rbcL')
  methList <- c('mcrA','mcrB','mcrG')
  aeroCODHList <- c('coxS','coxM','coxL')
  anaeroCODHList <- c('cooS_acsA','cdhE_acsC','cdhD_acsD','cdhC','cdhA','acsB')
  
  for (row in 1:nrow(dataframe)) {
    if (dataframe$Name[row] %in% rbcList) { 
      dataframe$Pathway[row] <- 'RuBiSCO'
    } else if (dataframe$Name[row] %in% methList) {
      dataframe$Pathway[row] <- 'Methanogenesis'
    } else if  (dataframe$Name[row] %in% aeroCODHList) {
      dataframe$Pathway[row] <- 'AerobicCODH'
    } else if  (dataframe$Name[row] %in% anaeroCODHList) {
      dataframe$Pathway[row] <- 'AnaerobicCODH'
    } else {
      print("Something is wrong")
    }}
  
  #Order x-axis samples, remove points for samples with zeros 
  SamplePlot <- dataframe[which(dataframe$tpm>0),] %>%
    mutate(Sample = fct_relevel(Sample, 
                                "D35.1","D33.1","D29.1","D56.1","D46.1","D12B.1","D67B.1",
                                "D33.2","D29.2","D46.2","D12B.2","D67B.2",
                                "D35.2","D35.3","D56.2","D56.3")) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=Sample, y=Name))
  
  ##Plot ggplot2 object, size bubbles is tpm, color is gene
  BubblePlot <- SamplePlot + 
    geom_count(aes(size=tpm, color=Pathway)) +
    theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
          panel.background = element_blank(), axis.line = element_line(colour = "black")) +
    scale_size(range = c(1,15))
  
  return(BubblePlot)
  
}

SampleRedoxPathBubblePlot <- function(dataframe){
  # return a bubble style plot for a gene abundance per Sample and Sample Grouping
  # Inputs: dataframe = raw data frame of gene abundance data formatted with colnames: Name, Sample, Group, tpm
  
  cols <- c('Name', 'Group')
  dataframe[cols] <- lapply(dataframe[cols], factor)
  
  ##Make $Pathway column
  
  RedoxList <- c('dsrB','dsrA','aprA','aprB')
  dataframe$Redox <- ifelse(dataframe$Name %in% RedoxList, 'Reduction', 'Oxidation')
  
  #Order x-axis samples, remove points for samples with zeros 
  SamplePlot <- dataframe[which(dataframe$tpm>0),] %>%
    mutate(Sample = fct_relevel(Sample, 
                                "D35.1","D33.1","D29.1","D56.1","D46.1","D12B.1","D67B.1",
                                "D33.2","D29.2","D46.2","D12B.2","D67B.2",
                                "D35.2","D35.3","D56.2","D56.3")) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=Sample, y=Name))
  
  ##Plot ggplot2 object, size bubbles is tpm, color is gene
  BubblePlot <- SamplePlot + 
    geom_count(aes(size=tpm, color=Redox)) +
    theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
          panel.background = element_blank(), axis.line = element_line(colour = "black")) +
    scale_size(range = c(1,15))
  
  return(BubblePlot)
  
}

#################### MAG "geom_tile()" Plot ####################################

#load data as MAG_Mods
head(MAG_Mods)

## row 505+ are empty
MAG_Mods <- MAG_Mods[1:504,] 

#Make ggplot Object

for (row in 1:nrow(MAG_Mods)) {
  if (MAG_Mods$Completeness[row] == 'complete') { 
    MAG_Mods$Value[row] <- 1
  } else if (MAG_Mods$Completeness[row] == 'partial') {
    MAG_Mods$Value[row] <- 0.5
  } else if  (MAG_Mods$Completeness[row] == 'none') {
    MAG_Mods$Value[row] <- 0
  } else {
    print("Something is wrong")
  }}

MAG_Mods$Value <- factor(MAG_Mods$Value)
MAG_Mods$Pathway <- factor(MAG_Mods$Pathway)


MAG_Mods <- MAG_Mods %>%
  mutate(Completeness = fct_relevel(Completeness, 'complete', 'partial', 'none'))

MAGPlot <- MAG_Mods %>%
  mutate(Pathway = fct_relevel(Pathway,
                            'Complex I',
                            'Cyt. c Oxidase',
                            'TCA cycle, 1st C Oxidation',
                            'TCA cycle, 2nd C Oxidation',
                            'RuBisCO',
                            'Aerobic CODH',
                            'Anaerobic CODH/ACS (acsACD)',
                            'Acetyl-CoA Synthetase (acs)',
                            'Acetyl-CoA Synthase (acsB)',
                            'Acetate Kinase',
                            'Phosphate Acetyltransferase',
                            'Sox System (soxABCXYZ)',
                            'Sulfide:quinone Reductase (SQR)',
                            'Nitrate Reductase (napAB or narGHI)',
                            'Nitrite Reductase (nirK)',
                            'Nitric Oxide Reductase (norBQ)',
                            'Nitrous Oxide Reductase (nosZ)',
                            'Nitrite Reductase (nirBD or nrfAH)')) %>%
  ggplot(aes(Bin, Pathway, fill=Value))



cols <- c("none" = "grey93", "partial" = "grey63", "complete" = "black")

MAGPlot + 
  geom_tile(aes(fill=Completeness), color = 'white') +
  scale_y_discrete(limits=rev) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = cols) +
  ggtitle("Metabolic Pathways and Complexes in BSF MAGs") +
  labs(fill = element_blank()) +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(),

Results¶

These results are discussed at length in a paper currently under review. You may access the preprint here: https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2021.10.18.464844v1. In additon to confirming the BSF has a robust and active ecosystem within and under the salt, these plots helped to gain insight into which metabolic processes are dominant at the BSF and identify which species are potentially involved in them. For example, the overview heatmap identifies sulfide and carbon monoxide oxidation as important and highly abundant processes that give microbes energy for growth. The macronutrient bubble plots show that genes involved in processes like methanogenesis and sulfate reduction are more abundant just below the salt, which makes sense as these are often associated with a lack of oxygen. The MAG plot shows diverse microbes contain a remarkable diversity of metabolic pathways, including those associated with carbon fixation, carbon monoxide oxidation, acetogenesis, methanogenesis, sulfide oxidation, denitrification, and nitrogen fixation. In general, these results demonstrate the potential for multiple energy sources and ecosystem functioning at the BSF and highlight the robust nature of life in the salt.
